  

<h2 id="now-that-journelly-can-write-directly-to-markdown-files-i-can-capture-notes-on-my-phone-and-have-them-in-my-obsidian-vault-on-my-mac-immediately-no-extra-steps.">Now that Journelly can write directly to Markdown files, I can capture notes on my phone and have them in my Obsidian vault on my Mac immediately ‚Äî no extra steps.</h2>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/bdb60c21-5acd-4ccd-bb9b-aa5cb4299eaf/pasted-percent20image-percent2020260126083714.png" alt="3 iphone screenshots showing Drafts, Journelly, and Obsidian side by side." width="2062" height="1458"> <em>Text on the screens in the image above is transcribed at the end of this post</em></p>
<hr>
<p>The biggest thing I want to do on my phone, after making calls, sending messages, and taking pictures, is to <strong><em>quickly</em></strong> <strong>write notes that I can <em>reliably</em> refer to on any other device</strong>.</p>
<p>The tools I use to do that are Drafts, Journelly, and Obsidian. In today‚Äôs post I‚Äôll tell you why I like each, and compare them all at the end.</p>
<h3 id="entering-quick-notes-with-drafts">Entering quick notes with Drafts</h3>
<p>Yes, Drafts is back in my rotation now that I know how to use it with Obsidian Sync. It‚Äôs even back in my iPhone dock!</p>
<p>Drafts was low friction before, and it‚Äôs even more so now that my most used actions appear right above the keyboard. I currently have 5 actions:</p>
<ul>
<li>1-N - for adding notes to my OBTF-successor, the 1-Note-Inbox. It adds the current date, day, and time, adds a blank line, and draws a horizontal rule between entries. Nice and neat.</li>
<li>todo - for adding tasks to my todo.txt document. It adds the current date and gives the task priority <code>(A)</code>, all in correct todo.txt syntax.</li>
<li>French - for adding flashcards as I come across a word or phrase I want to remember</li>
<li>Text - for sending what I‚Äôve written as a text message</li>
<li>Copy - for getting what I‚Äôve written onto the clipboard</li>
</ul>
<p>If you are using Drafts with Obsidian Sync on your iPhone, you‚Äôll need to <em>open Obsidian on your phone after completing a Drafts action</em> to let Obsidian Sync know that it‚Äôs there. My Drafts-entered iOS notes appear on my Mac less than 2 seconds after opening Obsidian on my phone.</p>
<h3 id="entering-quick-notes-with-journelly">Entering quick notes with Journelly</h3>
<p><a href="https://ellanew.com/2025/05/19/ptpl-157-journelly-is-org-for-those-who-dont-do-org" title="wikilink">In May last year</a> I described Journelly as<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>the first Org-powered app I‚Äôve seen that lays out the welcome mat for people who don‚Äôt even know what Org is, never mind how to use it.‚Äù</p>
<p>Since then, Journelly has released an update that gives you the option of storing your entries in either an Org (.org) or a Markdown (.md) file. It means that the file Journelly writes to can now be stored inside an Obsidian vault, even if you use Obsidian Sync!</p>
<p>To be clear: <strong>Journelly writes directly to a file that lives in my Obsidian vault</strong>. This is hugely significant! It means I can share web pages to Journelly, write a brief note about why I saved it, and add one of my task metadata (time, category) to any actions I want to take on the information. That metadata ensures I‚Äôll see it during my next review session. <em>All in one step, all without opening Obsidian.</em></p>
<p>With both Drafts and Journelly available on the Share Sheet, it‚Äôs interesting to note when I am drawn to one or the other. A few moments ago I chose Journelly over both Raindrop and Drafts when saving an article I‚Äôll want to reference later, to avoid an extra processing step. One motion and it‚Äôs in my system.</p>
<p>Journelly suggests and can autocomplete existing tags as I type them. In Drafts I have to remember my tags and be sure to type them the same way each time.</p>
<p>I love being able to see Journelly entries show up in my task query lists, just by using my customised todo.txt syntax. If something I‚Äôve entered or shared into Journelly needs looking at on a specific date, I preface that date with a colon and it shows up in my text-based planner right when it needs to. (Details on this plugin-free plain task text management method will be published some time this year.)</p>
<p>To point Journelly to an Obsidian vault on your iPhone, press the 3 dots at the bottom of the screen and select Storage from the menu. Then select Other, scroll down, and Move Data. From there you need to navigate to On My Phone, find Obsidian, and select your vault.</p>
<h3 id="entering-quick-notes-with-obsidian">Entering ~~<del>quick</del> notes with Obsidian</h3>
<p><a href="https://ellanew.com/2025/10/06/ptpl-176-simple-obsidian-iphone-shortcuts" title="wikilink">Home screen shortcuts</a> have sped up entering notes directly into my Obsidian vault, but it‚Äôs not as quick as Journelly or as flexible as Drafts. I‚Äôm aware that there are specialised, sophisticated shortcuts available that can do pretty much everything; I haven‚Äôt gone down that route because I haven‚Äôt felt the need to. If you are interested in learning more about how to get superpowers with Apple Shortcuts + Obsidian, check out <a href="https://actions.work/actions-for-obsidian/" target="_blank">Actions For Obsidian</a>.</p>
<p>I generally only type directly into Obsidian on my phone when working on a project, or adding events to my planner.</p>
<h3 id="comparing-obsidian-drafts-and-journelly">Comparing Obsidian, Drafts, and Journelly</h3>
<p>This comparison is from the perspective of quickly entering notes and making them available to my synced Apple devices.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th><em>Feature</em></th>
<th>Drafts</th>
<th>Journelly</th>
<th>Obsidian</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Price</td>
<td>‚≠ê Yearly subscription if you want custom actions</td>
<td><span class="small-caps">‚≠ê‚≠ê</span> One-off cost (excellent value)</td>
<td><span class="small-caps">‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê</span> Free, but better with Obsidian Sync</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Friction</td>
<td><span class="small-caps">‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê</span> Open the app, start typing</td>
<td><span class="small-caps">‚≠ê‚≠ê</span> Open the app, press <code>+</code>, start typing</td>
<td>‚≠ê Open the app or a file, tap to edit, start typing</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Distraction potential</td>
<td><span class="small-caps">‚≠ê‚≠ê</span> Depends. Low, once you‚Äôre set up. Customising actions can be majorly distracting.</td>
<td><span class="small-caps">‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê</span> The clear winner - all you can do is type. Brilliant.</td>
<td>‚≠ê Obsidian can be used simply, but it‚Äôs easy to be sucked into customising almost every aspect.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Features</td>
<td>Text can be sent anywhere, preformatted with variables</td>
<td>Does one thing, and does it well</td>
<td>Sky is the limit, which can be a distraction</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>There are other plain text ways to enter text quickly on iOS and have it show up on a Mac. Let me know about any workflows you are particularly fond of.</p>
<p>If you end up buying and enjoying Journelly, spread the news! Let‚Äôs support an indie app maker who is choosing to stay away from the subscription model. Contact the developer (Xenodium) to request trial access to the beta if you want to check it out first.</p>
<hr>
<p><em>Text from the first image, above:</em></p>
<p><em>Drafts</em></p>
<ul>
<li><em>Markdown friendly</em></li>
<li><em>Works with Obsidian Sync</em></li>
<li><em>Not a good place to store notes</em></li>
<li><em>Great place to start writing text that needs to go somewhere</em></li>
</ul>
<p><em>Journelly</em></p>
<ul>
<li><em>Lets you store notes with the Markdown extension, not write notes with Markdown formatting</em></li>
<li><em>Suggests tags so you don‚Äôt have to remember them</em></li>
<li><em>Displays images with your text</em></li>
<li><em>Files can live inside an Obsidian vault</em></li>
</ul>
<p><em>Obsidian</em></p>
<ul>
<li><em>A polished interface for your locally stored files</em></li>
<li><em>Not good for quick notes without outside help</em></li>
<li><em>If I could only choose one, Obsidian would win hands down</em></li>
</ul>
